(761, 6, '2015-05-08 14:45:46', '2015-05-08 14:45:46', 'I started out in business at the tender (and slightly naive) age of 14 and have always wanted to run a business and achieve goals. I set about this whilst at University, which in hindsight probably wasnt the most sensible option but we all have to start somewhere, and decided to combine my passion for emergency medicine and creativity by forming Jigsaw Medical. I wouldn’t have it any other way, so I’ve decided to talk through my 5 top reasons for starting your own company…\n\n1) <strong>Make your own decisions.</strong> I’m not one to make decisions without consulting my team, but I love having a direct impact on the culture and future of my company. This leads into my second reason…\n\n2) <strong>Creativity</strong>. Having the ability to create our own opportunities and brand is amazing, our brand at Jigsaw Medical has become very recognisable and I’m very proud of how it has developed and become a sign of quality in the medical industry.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/JMS-Logo-PNG1.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-770\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/JMS-Logo-PNG1.png\" alt=\"JMS Logo (PNG)\" width=\"1002\" height=\"239\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Screen-Shot-2015-05-08-at-10.32.52.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-767\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Screen-Shot-2015-05-08-at-10.32.52.png\" alt=\"jigsaw-branding\" width=\"1002\" height=\"657\" /></a>\n\n3) <strong>Doing what you enjoy</strong>. I work long hours but do it for something I’m passionate about it doesn’t feel like work (most of the time!). I imagine there is nothing worse than dreading going to work everyday and I am lucky enough not have to worry about that.\n\n4) <strong>Picking my own team.</strong> I get to choose exactly who I want to work with. As I stated earlier we will always employ someone if we believe they can do a job for #TeamJigsaw, however I have to feel that they are willing to invest in the ethos of the company. As a result I like to think (and I hope our team would agree) that coming to work at Jigsaw House is enjoyable and not something you dread on a Sunday evening.\n\n5) <strong>Being a mentor</strong>. As Jigsaw has grown and become more successful I was to be a mentor for <a title=\"Virgin Startup\" href=\"http://www.virginstartup.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Virgin Startup</a> helping new entrepreneurs on their journey helping young entrepreneurs on their journey into owning their own business. If done right there’s a lot of enjoyment that can come from watching someone develop and reach their full potential!\n\n6) Ok I said there was 5 but this one is important. <strong>Your reason.</strong> The list above details my reasons. if you’re reading this blog post you probably already have an interest in starting your own business. So, what is your reason? Share on social media and include your reason or comment below.\n\nWhat are you waiting for?', 'Why should you start your own business?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-reasons-to-start-your-own-business', '', '', '2015-05-08 14:45:46', '2015-05-08 14:45:46', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=761', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(787, 6, '2015-07-04 09:57:38', '2015-07-04 09:57:38', 'The sun is shining and the UK events season is up and running. That means that event organisers all over the UK will be implementing those plans to execute an amazing event.\n\nWith Jigsaw Medical\'s recent appointment of Richard McManus as \'Head of Events\', our capability and deliverabity has just got massive.\n\nAs you will always hear me say - \"it\'s about the right people, in the right places\" and Richard is no different, he joins #TeamJigsaw following a wide and varied career history. After serving in the Royal Navy for 7 years, he trained as an Aircraft Firefighter and medic serving in various destinations all over the world. Through this Richard become interested in pre-hospital medicine and on leaving the Navy joined the Yorkshire Ambulance Service and then North West Ambulance Service to complete his training.\n\nAs a Paramedic has been lucky enough to work on some of the UK\'s largest music events, sporting events and through this has developed a passion for event planning and medical management where he has been responsible for some of the UK\'s biggest events, such as V Festival. Richard particularly worked very closely with Jigsaw Medical last year as the primary link between the Tour de France and Jigsaw Medical teams and via this partnership a relationship developed which resulted in Richard taking on the \'Head of Events\' position in the Jigsaw Medical clinical team.\n\nOnce again this is a great step for Jigsaw in our event provision and a further 7 appointments over as many weeks have equally developed other areas of the business.', 'Event Season Underway!', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'event-season-underway', '', '', '2015-07-04 09:57:38', '2015-07-04 09:57:38', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=787', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(791, 6, '2015-07-04 11:04:48', '2015-07-04 11:04:48', '<h2><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/image2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright wp-image-796 size-medium\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/image2-e1436007648376-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"image\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>Our head office team has grown 6-fold since the beginning of the year.</h2>\nI am sat with Sammie this morning (with my very glamorous peppermint tea!), discussing the latest members of the Jigsaw team. Although Sammie remains adamant that she \"can\'t keep up\" with it all, I am proud to say that nearly 20 amazing people have joined our head office team in just 7 months. Joining them are over 100 ambulance clinicians working on our own ambulances and over 3,000 Nurses, Ambulance Clinicians, Paramedics and Doctors - all of which I am proud to say are part of #TeamJigsaw.\n\nAfter an exceptional start to 2015, we announced last week the appointment of Julie Mercer as our new Projects and Compliance Director. Julie joins Jigsaw Medical as a vastly experienced Director particularly within Project and Compliance leadership, and as a former Nurse and Operational Director for NHS Professionals she was responsible for the design, set up and implementation of the current “NHSP” organisation commissioned by the Department Of Health becoming the largest ‘in-house’ national temporary staff provider of the NHS. Before joining Jigsaw, she worked for a £500million recruitment business in a similar role, so not only can she do an amazing job, she is able to do it on a huge scale (which is exactly where we are hoping to be).\n\nAlong with Julie, we have recently had a further 7 members of the team join our head office in as many weeks. Richard McManus (who I wrote about in my <a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/event-season-underway/\">post on the event season</a>) – is a Paramedic and former Medical Manager for events such as ‘V Festival’ and the ‘Tour de France’, he joins as Head of Events and will be responsible for leading our team of event managers to deliver and develop medical provision to some of the UK’s largest events.\n\nJon Shield has been appointed to lead our Specialist Operations Division, which is an exciting new division that will be launching in August 2015. As well as recently completing his Paramedic Degree, Jon has extensive military background serving in the Parachute Regiment, and has also worked in the private sector on Close Protection, Maritime and hostile environment deployments across the globe.\n\nFurthermore, Sian Jeffery and Elliot Finney have joined Jigsaw as Recruitment Consultants to facilitate the growth within our recruitment division, and deal with the increasing demands faced of an ever expanding client-base. Additionally, Elinor Parry has joined our Training Division to facilitate the range of additional courses we are offering this year. Jan Pomfret joins our compliance team from a position with the UK Doctor\'s regulator, the GMC. Finally, Lisa Walker joins our Accounts &amp; Payroll team to support the day-to-day finance requirements and the payroll of thousands of people every week.\n<h3>It\'s about foundations...</h3>\nI was recently honoured to be asked to speak at a recent event hosted by <a href=\"http://www.ukfast.co.uk\">UKFast</a>. Lawrence Jones (CEO of UKFast) asked me to join him and two other entrepreneurs to share our experiences for their #InspireMCR event. One thing struck me during Lawrence\'s talk was one analogy which really hit home with me and the strategy we so strongly adopted at Jigsaw - which was \"the stronger your foundations, the higher your building will be\".\n\nUp until recently, both our compliance and accounts teams had more people in than our sales teams in any of our divisions. We could have easily taken on loads of great sales people between the beginning of the year and now, but we didn\'t. The reason? - because we wanted our foundations to be strong enough to support our huge plans for the coming years.\n\nYou will notice that many of these recent appointments are very much \'sales\' focused because now we have those very strong foundations in place, we can really start to make an even bigger dint on the market than we already have.\n\nNo longer is Jigsaw Medical simply the vision of a 23 year old graduate Paramedic. We have inspirational people who share this vision. Our foundations consist of the very best people, in all of the right places. From an ex-CEO of a £580million group to management trainers. From Chartered Accountants to Consultant Anaesthetists, from vastly experienced NHS compliance Directors to the very best recruitment consultants, sales team, PR professionals, clinical educators and operational and clinical management professionals.\n\nAll of this makes #TeamJigsaw very special... the rest of 2015 and going into 2016 is going to be an awesome experience for everyone who is on-board the Jigsaw rocket ship!\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/4d3c1c5bf36fa.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-605\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/4d3c1c5bf36fa.jpg\" alt=\"4d3c1c5bf36fa\" width=\"600\" height=\"445\" /></a>', 'Building Foundations & Growing The Team', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'building-foundations-growing-the-team', '', '', '2015-07-04 11:04:48', '2015-07-04 11:04:48', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=791', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(798, 6, '2015-07-09 15:11:39', '2015-07-09 15:11:39', '<h2><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/disruption-300x196.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-799\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/disruption-300x196-300x196.jpg\" alt=\"disruption-300x196\" width=\"300\" height=\"196\" /></a>Everyone seems to be talking about \'disruption\' at the moment, but what does it mean?</h2>\nI\'ve heard an increasing rumble about disruption over the last few months, in fact it was only a couple of weeks ago I looked into it properly, after I was told by our PR team at <a href=\"www.jigsawmedical.com\">Jigsaw Medical</a> that Lawrence Jones (CEO at UKFast) had mentioned us in his speech at the \"IOD Disruptor\" conference in Manchester.\n\nWhen I watched it back to make sure Lawrence was being nice about us (which I never doubted, for the record), there were some amazing \'takes\' on disruption and how powerful it is in businesses, especially in this new world of huge technological capability and what seems to be a more enterprising culture than the past few years.\n\nAfter a bit of digging, I noticed that Richard Branson had setup \'Virgin Disruptor\'s\' with Holly (his daughter) which essentially debated areas of \'disruption\' and focused on entrepreneurs being \'open minded\' in order to become a \'disruptor\'.\n\nA <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/carolinehoward/2013/03/27/you-say-innovator-i-say-disruptor-whats-the-difference/\">recent post by Forbes</a> claimed that people are sometimes confused about the difference between innovation and disruption. \"It’s not exactly black and white, but there are real distinctions, and it’s not just splitting hairs.\" They said to \"think of it this way: Disruptors are innovators, but not all innovators are disruptors — in the same way that a square is a rectangle but not all rectangles are squares\"... (at this point, you have to stick with it).... Innovation and disruption are similar in that they are both makers and builders. Disruption takes a left turn by literally uprooting and changing how we think, behave, do business, learn and go about our day-to-day.\n<h3>Do Jigsaw disrupt?</h3>\nTo be honest, I think we have done so since the beginning - without really knowing it. I\'d like to say that we have started to change how private organisations within the healthcare sector operate and are perceived. Without going on forever, I can think of a few examples of how we have \'disrupted the market\'. One example is being the only fully self-sufficient ambulance provider in the private sector, with the ability to educate internally right up to Paramedic degree level, including the relevant on-the-job training (the only company in that position). Another example would be to utilise Health Care Professionals in \'out of the box ways\', such as putting Paramedics in operating theatres.\n\nThe vision for everyone in Jigsaw is big, it\'s to make a huge impact on the healthcare sector, with maximum quality healthcare in a creative and innovative way, embracing technology in the process.\n\nThat\'s the stamp we want to leave on the UK and eventually the world... so if that\'s what you call \'disruption\' in the market, then I am proud to say we are \'disruptor\'s\' (in the nicest possible way).', 'Everyone is talking about disruption', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'disruption', '', '', '2015-07-09 15:11:39', '2015-07-09 15:11:39', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=798', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(803, 6, '2015-08-05 10:07:06', '2015-08-05 10:07:06', '<h2><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/CLoIoM5WcAA-A9_.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-804\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/CLoIoM5WcAA-A9_-286x300.jpg\" alt=\"CLoIoM5WcAA-A9_\" width=\"286\" height=\"300\" /></a>\"Money is a byproduct of success\"</h2>\nYou will often here this quote from entrepreneurs and it is certainly one I can relate to. Whilst everyone needs to earn a living, I like many entrepreneurs didn\'t start my business to \"make lots of money\" and in actual fact, I have never measured the success of Jigsaw in how much money we have been making, rather I use our level of revenue as a guide to see how we are growing.\n\nPersonally, I think a leader needs to be \'visionary\' rather than exclusively money and performance focused, they need to see the \'bigger picture\' and drive the \'purpose\' of the business. I truly believe that if entrepreneurs hold this as a core value, the money will follow as a byproduct.\n<h2>Does everyone need to forget about the money?</h2>\nAbsolutely not. Whilst it is vital for \'visionary\' entrepreneurs to stay focused on the purpose and \'bigger picture\', every business needs to make money to survive and in actual fact, they need the exact opposite to themselves in order to succeed.\n\nAccountants clearly need to focus on the money, where it goes and make sure any business has enough of it to meet the vision of the leader - but this concept goes beyond them.\n\nIn Jigsaw, I would classify myself as \'visionary\' rather than money focused, I would rather spend money on making Jigsaw better, than putting it in my personal bank account. However, without my money driven counter parts in our Sales and Recruitment teams - nothing would ever happen! Equally, we need the Clinical teams to be focused on quality, rather than money and so they are not afraid of getting the latest equipment. It is this blend which has got Jigsaw to where it is.\n<h2>So is \"Money is a byproduct of success\"?</h2>\nAbsolutely. But only when you have the right blend of people, with their own reasons for doing what they are doing - which does actually include, in the likes of our recruitment &amp; sales teams, them being money focused.\n\n&nbsp;', 'How much money is success?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-much-money-is-success', '', '', '2015-08-05 10:07:06', '2015-08-05 10:07:06', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=803', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(808, 6, '2015-08-18 12:56:03', '2015-08-18 12:56:03', '<h3>With the Labour leadership campaign representing a large proportion of the national media coverage at the moment I thought it would be a good time to write an article about leadership.</h3>\nDon\'t worry I\'m not going to write an article about politics, and whilst I don\'t agree with Jeremy Corbyn on quite a few of his policies there does seem to be some distinct reasons as to why he is garnering so much support and momentum, and those reasons can be easily applied to leading in the work place.\n<h3>1) Honesty</h3>\nWhether it be business or politics, being open and honest is a key attribute of a good leader. Here at #TeamJigsaw I always do my best to be honest with all of my team, irrespective of their level in the \'hierarchy\', about the performance and direction of the company. The team are a direct reflection of myself and the company so if I am honest and ethical with them, they will follow suit, and that will come across to clients and customers alike.\n<h3>2) Communication</h3>\nI am very clear what I want to achieve with Jigsaw and much of it is a shared vision of where we want to be. Ultimately that is to be the best supplier of medical staff and clinical / healthcare services in the world, whilst also providing the highest quality of care to our customer, clients and ultimately the patients. At #TeamJigsaw there are no secrets. All of the team know exactly what we want to achieve and having these defined goal helps us all work towards it with more confidence.\n<h3>3) Passion</h3>\nLike the above I am extremely passionate about Jigsaw Medical and the quality of care we provide, particularly to patients that our ambulance crews and medical staff deal with on a day-to-day basis. I\'m not backwards in coming forwards in sharing and conveying my passion and what we want to achieve, and I think this helps other members of #TeamJigsaw buy into the ethos of the company. Well we\'ve never had a member of staff leave so we must be doing something right!\n<h3>4) Commitment</h3>\nIf you want people to work hard for you and your company you must put the work in yourself and lead by example. I\'m usually one of the first in the office in the morning and one of the last out in the evening. I believe that people see my commitment to the cause and I like to think that this motivates people to do the same. Additionally, I am committed to making Jigsaw House and our other 5 offices an enjoyable place to come to everyday, which helps keep morale and motivation high within the company, and in turn helps people deliver the highest quality of work possible.\n<h3>5) Optimism</h3>\nThis is possibly my favourite and the most important. A leader has to be optimistic. The best leaders in the world and particularly the ones who have inspired me (Richard Branson and Lawrence Jones) are some of the most optimistic people you will ever meet. They\'re always a source of positive energy and you can see a reflection of them in the staff that work for them. When there is a problem at Jigsaw I don\'t dwell on the problems but always try to provide a positive solution and find the right things to do to inspire and reassure.\n\nObviously there are countless other attributes that contribute to being a good leader, the above list is not the be all and end all. My team may tell you differently (I hope not!!) but I like to think I\'m doing a good job at leading #TeamJigsaw in the right direction. However, there isn\'t one right answer, you have to be able to constantly learn and evolve, but if you\'re successful and your team support you, you\'re probably doing it right!', 'Leadership - What makes a good leader?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'leadership-what-makes-a-good-leader', '', '', '2015-08-18 12:56:03', '2015-08-18 12:56:03', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=808', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(818, 6, '2015-10-05 08:34:22', '2015-10-05 08:34:22', '<h2><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/42_u_42_logo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-819\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/42_u_42_logo.jpg\" alt=\"42_u_42_logo\" width=\"160\" height=\"105\" /></a>Every year Insider Media publish their \'42 Under 42\' list...</h2>\nThis year, I am super proud to have been included in the <a href=\"http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/north-west/148763-insider-reveals-42-under-42-list/\">class of 2015</a>, this is certainly testament to the efforts of the whole of #TeamJigsaw, both in our HQ, regional offices and of course the Paramedics, Doctors, Nurses and Ambulance Clinician\'s we have out treating patients across the UK.\n\nChris Maguire, editor of <em>North West Business Insider</em>, said: \"These are the people who we feel are the ones to watch. The class of 2015 is packed full of inspirational entrepreneurs. Age has been no barrier to their success and we congratulate them all.\"\n\nI am proud to be the youngest on the list this year, but the fact remains that it is not \"me\" who has secured a place on this prestigious list - I am simply accepting it on behalf of the whole of #TeamJigsaw who have got us to where we are today - so thank you!\n\n<em>North West Business Insider</em>\'s 42 Under 42 list is sponsored by Saffery Champness and the University of Bolton.', '42 under 42...', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', '42-under-42', '', '', '2015-10-05 08:34:22', '2015-10-05 08:34:22', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=818', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(827, 6, '2015-12-15 15:56:39', '2015-12-15 15:56:39', '<h3>2015 has been a special year for Jigsaw Medical but the final 6 months have been particularly impressive with multi-million-pound investment, life-saving treatment and unprecedented growth.</h3>\nSince June, Jigsaw Medical have added over 30 brand new fully-kitted ambulances to the already expansive fleet as well as 8 brand new response vehicles that help supplement the ambulances clinically. In order to house the new vehicles, multiple operational offices have been established across the UK that act as bases for crew members to work from in a whole host of different areas.\n\nAs well as operational expansion, Jigsaw medical has always been a keen “Investor in People” and in the previous 6 months, the head office (Jigsaw House) in Tarporley has seen 8 new people successfully join the team with 2 new members set to join the New Year.\n\nThe last 6 months have also seen 2 new Directors join the company; Julie Mercer joined the team in late summer as Projects and Compliance Director. Julie joined Jigsaw Medical as a vastly experienced Director particularly within Project and Compliance leadership within the NHS. Additionally, Richard McManus was appointed Director of Clinical Services in July (after previously holding the Head of Events position) and brought with him a wealth of medical and event organisation experience.\n\nRichard stated: “It’s been an eventful but ultimately extremely fruitful end to 2015. With over 600 clinicians successfully registering and becoming fully compliant in that period. Coupled with over £3 million invested in gold standard equipment and vehicles we have managed to amass in excess of 250,000 hours worked by the Jigsaw team.”\n\n“And in that period, with the expertise, knowledge and equipment that our crews are armed with, as well as other key performance indicators, we have been responsible for 8 ROSCs (Return of Spontaneous Circulation) and the safe delivery of at least 5 babies. Without the incredible investment and team that we have at Jigsaw none of that would have been possible.”', 'Incredible 6 months at Jigsaw Medical!', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'incredible-6-months-at-jigsaw-medical', '', '', '2015-12-15 15:56:39', '2015-12-15 15:56:39', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=827', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(832, 6, '2015-12-31 12:55:17', '2015-12-31 12:55:17', '<h3>As 2015 comes to a close, its time to reflect on the year that\'s passed and set goals for the year ahead...</h3>\nFor me, 2015 has been an incredible year - fast paced to say the least. In just one year we have grown over 500% on the previous year which is all thanks to our amazing team and of course our clients. 2015 has seen over 2,200 new clinicians registering to work with Jigsaw Medical, we have invested over £3 million in gold standard equipment and vehicles we have managed to amass in excess of 750,000 hours worked by the Jigsaw team... our Ambulance crews have even delivered over 10 babies into the world!\n\nOn a personal level, it has been amazing to continue to build our leadership team and see Jigsaw, in just 4 years, going from the University bedroom startup it once was, to a multi-million pound business.\n<h4><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/teamjigsaw.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-836\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/teamjigsaw-300x60.png\" alt=\"teamjigsaw\" width=\"300\" height=\"60\" /></a>My very own New Year\'s Honors List....</h4>\nThe \'Jigsaw Medical\' we have today is only here because of the team and those who have helped me (and the business) along the journey so far, I would like to thank absolutely all of the team who are such a massive part of Jigsaw in their own ways and in their respective divisions....\n<ul>\n	<li>To the Directors who keep everything (including me) in check - I don\'t know what I would do without these amazing guys!</li>\n	<li>The Jigsaw House; recruitment, compliance, finance, training, clinical, operations and communications teams</li>\n	<li>To the Area Operations teams who keep our operational bases running smoothly 24/7</li>\n	<li>Our Clinical Governance Team who make sure our patients get the very best clinical care</li>\n	<li>Our Fleet Engineers who work 24/7 keeping our vehicles on the road</li>\n	<li>... and of course; the Paramedics, Emergency Care Assistants, Technicians, Nurses and Doctors who represent Jigsaw and deliver this exceptional care to our patients... you are all amazing and without you, there would be no Jigsaw!</li>\n</ul>\nAlong with our own team, I would like to thank our suppliers for keeping us well stocked in 2015 (specifically <a href=\"http://www.spservices.co.uk\">SP Services</a>) and all those organisations who continue to support Jigsaw\'s growth. I would also like to thank all those who continue to support me personally through guidance, mentorship and support; including my family (Mum, Dad &amp; Sister, Rob, Laurie and of course Sammie!) and last but not least... <a href=\"http://www.lawrencejones.eu/\">Lawrence Jones </a>for the mentorship, support, guidance and inspiration! - I cannot begin to tell you all how much of a difference this has made!\n<h4><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/2016-new-year-ss-1920.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-835\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/2016-new-year-ss-1920-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"2016-new-year-ss-1920\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" /></a>Into 2016...</h4>\nWe have some big - in fact, very big plans for 2016. Whilst I am so proud of growing over 500% this year, the plans for 2016 will see this be even higher compared with this year. However, as a fast growing business, we have learn\'t many lessons and we have had to adapt to demand and continue to improve, innovate and make things better - this is something we will continue as an ethos into 2016.\n\nWe have a continuous recruitment drive to support several new contracts starting in early 2016 and we hope to expand even more across the UK, particularly in strengthening our ambulance operations (so if you are reading this and fancy a new challenge in 2016, <a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/contact-chris/\">get in touch</a>!). To further support this, we will build many more brand new, gold-standard vehicles for our crews to work with. Our clinical governance team will continue to drive clinical innovations and continue to hold our patients and the very forefront of what we do.\n<h4>Tomorrow is the start of your 365 page book....</h4>\n(When I posted this amazing quote on Twitter this morning, within 40seconds I was corrected... 2016 is of course a leap-year, so you actually get 366!!)\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/CXjGGw4WQAArmSZ1.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-834\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/CXjGGw4WQAArmSZ1-300x240.jpg\" alt=\"CXjGGw4WQAArmSZ\" width=\"300\" height=\"240\" /></a>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">What are your goals for 2016?... what is written in your book?</h3>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Have an amazing New Year\'s eve and I will see you all in 2016!</h2>\n&nbsp;', 'What a year it\'s been!', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-a-year-its-been', '', '', '2015-12-31 12:55:17', '2015-12-31 12:55:17', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=832', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(843, 6, '2016-02-17 09:12:17', '2016-02-17 09:12:17', 'Late last year I was honoured to be invited to be a participant in an annual event called MicroBizMattersDay. In a nutshell, MicroBizMattersDay is a global, annual day of actions. Everyone is asked to give at least 8 minutes, day or night, to make life better for micro enterprise (0-9 employees) owners everywhere.\n\n<strong>Why I Support #MicroBizMattersDay...</strong>\n\nI was very excited to be supporting #MicroBizMattersDay and it’s a cause that I am particularly passionate about. Having been introduced to Tony at an awards ceremony in 2014 I have closely followed Tony and Tina and #MicroBizMatters, and how it highlights the contribution independent business owners and self-employed people make, not only to the growth of this country’s economy but to the global economy.\n\nAdditionally, startups such as the company I own, Jigsaw Medical, contribute not only to the local economy by providing jobs and security for staff, we also provide a fantastic service to the general public through the provision of highly skilled staff and brand new, state-of-the-art equipment and ambulances.\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Tony and Tina do a fantastic job advocating the importance of the small business and startups, again something that particularly resonates with myself.</p>\n</blockquote>\nWhen I launched my business back in 2012 I was lucky enough to have a lot of help and support from experienced people as well as some fantastic family and friends. But not everyone is lucky enough to have that, so as a result, I can’t wait for January 8th where hopefully I can impart some nuggets of wisdom and advice to other micro-businesses, whilst also gaining crucial advice and tips on different things I can do to help me run my businesses.\n\n<strong>The Day</strong>\n\nOn the day, I took part in an hour-long webchat with other entrepreneurs and microbiz owners during the Enterprising Young People Hour and found the whole experience fantastic. Being able to impart some wisdom and pick up some tips for myself was exceptionally useful.\n\nCheck out the video of the web chat. I’m on from 1 hour 52 minutes if that’s what takes your fancy! (I\'m sure it isnt...)\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cPHyztZLi-k\n\nOverall it was a great day to be a part of and I hope to be involved next year.', 'MicroBizMatters Day & Enterprise Rocks', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'microbizmatters-day-enterprise-rocks', '', '', '2016-02-17 09:12:17', '2016-02-17 09:12:17', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=843', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(849, 6, '2016-03-08 18:44:32', '2016-03-08 18:44:32', '<strong>After providing medical support to the Virgin STRIVE Challenge in 2014, I am delighted that we have gone one step further for 2016 and will be one of the key sponsors of this year’s <a href=\"http://bigchange.strivechallenge.com\">Virgin STRIVE Challenge</a>. </strong>\n\nFor those that don’t know about the challenge, it was set up in 2014 by Sam Branson and cousin Noah Devereux and involves a team of people testing themselves via a series of ultra-endurance challenges, all to raise funds for the charity, <a href=\"http://big-change.org\">Big Change</a> which was founded in 2012 by Holly and Sam Branson, Princess Beatrice of York, Sam Richardson, Phil Nevin, and Isabella Branson. It\'s goal - to think differently about the role that charity can play in driving change for young people in the UK. The charity aims to do more than just treating symptoms, they wanted to positively move things forward, backing solutions that demonstrate alternative ways of supporting young people- helping them to thrive in life, not just in exams.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.jigsawmedical.com/wp-content/uploads/MG_7716.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-6125 aligncenter\" src=\"https://www.jigsawmedical.com/wp-content/uploads/MG_7716.jpg\" alt=\"virgin-strive-bigchange-2016\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" /></a>\n\nIn 2014, we provided the ambulances, medical staff, and equipment, whilst a 10-strong team hiked, ran, rowed, cycled climbed from London to the summit of the Matterhorn in Switzerland. The 2016 challenge picks up where the 2014 challenge ended and sees a team of 25 tackle a punishing 30-day journey from the base of the Matterhorn to Mount Etna in Sicily, all whilst being looked after by #TeamJigsaw’s expert team of Doctors, Paramedics, Ambulances and Physiotherapists.\n\nI am so proud to see Jigsaw supporting this amazing charity!', 'Jigsaw Sponsors The Virgin STRIVE Challenge 2016', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'supporting-virgin-strive-challenge', '', '', '2016-03-08 18:44:32', '2016-03-08 18:44:32', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=849', 0, 'post', '', 0);
