(1515, 1, '2017-05-19 10:12:22', '2017-05-19 10:12:22', 'Nested and mixed lists are an interesting beast. It\'s a corner case to make sure that\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height:1.714285714;font-size:1rem;\">Lists within lists do not break the ordered list numbering order</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height:1.714285714;font-size:1rem;\">Your list styles go deep enough.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Ordered - Unordered - Ordered</h3>\n<ol>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n	<li>ordered item\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>unordered</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>unordered</strong>\n<ol>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Ordered - Unordered - Unordered</h3>\n<ol>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n	<li>ordered item\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>unordered</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>unordered</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n	<li>ordered item</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Unordered - Ordered - Unordered</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item\n<ol>\n	<li>ordered</li>\n	<li>ordered\n<ul>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Unordered - Unordered - Ordered</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item\n<ul>\n	<li>unordered</li>\n	<li>unordered\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>ordered item</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>ordered item</strong></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n	<li>unordered item</li>\n</ul>', 'Edge Case: Nested And Mixed Lists', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1000-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-19 10:12:22', '2017-05-19 10:12:22', '', 1000, 'http://localhost/ChrisPercival/2017/05/19/1000-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1518, 6, '2015-03-23 11:33:50', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/teamjigsaw.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-568\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/teamjigsaw.png\" alt=\"teamjigsaw\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1068\" /></a>', '', '', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-03-23 11:33:50', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=730', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1519, 6, '2014-10-09 10:47:27', '2014-10-09 10:47:27', '<div>\n<h2>Suppliers can seriously affect the quality of your products/services and your ability to deliver on your promises!</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/creditscore.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-560\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/creditscore.png\" alt=\"creditscore\" width=\"1055\" height=\"350\" /></a><em>This check was done just now, comparing our credit check (on the right), with one of our competitors (left) – obviously we won\'t tell you which stone you would find them under! - <strong>but the difference is clear!</strong>\n</em></p>\nIf a supplier lets you down, you let your customers down (or in our business, your patients could be at risk). This can damage your business\' or NHS Trusts reputation and cause clinical or operational problems. Choosing a supplier without seeing their business report could cost you, or worse, your patients.\n\nGetting a business report to check suppliers helps establish their stability and their ability to provide a quality service, in both the medium and long term. Choosing a reliable, financially stable supplier means that you can be confident you can always fulfil commitments to your customers.\n<h4>A supplier check can help you choose the right people to work with</h4>\nBusiness Check from Experian allows you to take an inside look at your current or potential suppliers – that’s what we use!\n<strong>A business report lets you check suppliers by seeing information on:</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>The stability of suppliers by seeing their credit score</li>\n	<li>The future reliability of suppliers with alerts on any changes in their status</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>With accurate information from a supplier check profile, you can make the right choices for your patients, Trust or business!</strong></h3>\n</div>', 'How important is the financial stability of your suppliers?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'important-financial-stability-suppliers', '', '', '2014-10-09 10:47:27', '2014-10-09 10:47:27', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=559', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1520, 6, '2014-11-05 17:54:43', '2014-11-05 17:54:43', '<h2>I recently had an interesting debate with some of my family about what I should wear to meetings...</h2>\n<strong>My general rule has always been Suits &amp; Ties are for Weddings, Funerals and Court... those in <a href=\"http://www.jigsawmedical.com\">Jigsaw Medical</a> and my family know this well and when I occasionally do put a suit on, they get very concerned indeed!</strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/0210-MARK-ZUCKERBERG-sized.jpg_full_600.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-583\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/0210-MARK-ZUCKERBERG-sized.jpg_full_600-161x300.jpg\" alt=\"0210-MARK-ZUCKERBERG-sized.jpg_full_600\" width=\"161\" height=\"300\" /></a>I personally think there are no rules about suits, ties and any of the other 60\'s contraptions that people think constitute \'business wear\'. I honestly think that gone are the days of Directors and business people wearing suits. My rule has always been that people dress smartly but more importantly, comfortably... maybe one day we will do some experiment to prove my theory that comfortable people work more efficiently, happily and enjoy going to work more - but to me, its common sense.\n\nDon\'t get me wrong, I believe in people being smart, but I would never insist on someone wearing a suit... and certainly not a tie! (I do share <a href=\"http://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/why-it%E2%80%99s-time-to-say-bye-to-the-tie\">Mr Branson\'s view on ties</a>!). Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg, the late Steve Jobs and Richard Branson (to name a few) do not wear traditional suits... I really <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">don\'t</span> believe there is science in this next statement, but look how creative, forward thinking and successful these three people are and have been! I recently met Richard Reed (the Founder of Innocent Drinks), again he was in a t-shirt a jeans - another hugely creative and successful guy... maybe that\'s because they worked in comfort?\n\nIf I existed in business 25 years ago (or was even born), I am sure my view may be different - but then again as was the world, technology and the existence of small businesses to the extent they are today. To some extent I think people wear what they have been brought up to wear.\n\nI don\'t wear a suit (if I can help it), that\'s not me being arrogant, its me being comfortable so I can perform my best. Those who disagree with my dress code often say they don\'t feel at work without a suit on, in which case they may well feel more comfortable in a suit! (but I would urge them to try the jeans, shirt and suit jacket attire!)\n<h4>Some will agree, some will disagree, but as long as people are smart, comfortable and happy - that sounds good to me!</h4>', 'Business Dress Code... Suit or Jeans?...', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'business-dress-code-suit-jeans', '', '', '2014-11-05 17:54:43', '2014-11-05 17:54:43', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=582', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1521, 6, '2015-03-12 11:46:26', '2015-03-12 11:46:26', '<h3>After unprecedented growth of 382% and an increase in profits of 213% in 2014, #TeamJigsaw is happy to announce the appointment of a new PR &amp; Social Media Manager and a new Recruitment Consultant for our Nurses department.</h3>\nNeil Coleman and Matt Jones are appointed to the respective posts of PR and Social Media Manager, and Recruitment Consultant. Neil was looking for a career change and joins us after completing a 3 month internship, having previously had more than seven years in customer service and account management. Matt joins #TeamJigsaw\'s nurse recruitment division after 14 years’ in sales and customer service.\n\nAs well as these new additions we are looking to add to the team, and are currently recruiting candidates for two new roles; a <a title=\"Recruitment Compliance Administrator Job Description\" href=\"http://www.jigsawmedical.com/connect/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Compliance-Administrator.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Recruitment Compliance Administrator</a> and an <a title=\"Accounts/Payroll Administrator Job Description\" href=\"http://www.jigsawmedical.com/connect/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Accounts-Payroll-Administrator.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Accounts/Payroll Administrator</a>.\n\nThe role of Recruitment Compliance Administrator would suit some who ideally has experience within the medical or recruitment industry, is able to work flexibly but office-based, has exceptional organisational skills and has interest in planning their own time effectively. They will be working with healthcare professionals to ensure their documentation is stored correctly onto an in-house database.\n\nAdditionally, the Accounts/Payroll Administrator role would suit someone who ideally has experience of operating the payroll and raising invoices within the medical or recruitment industry and is an excellent communicator with good organisational skills.\n\nI\'m a firm believe that people are at the heart of our success. We are proud of our creative and positive working environment, and strive to make sure our team enjoy coming to work.\n\nJigsaw was built on foundations of transparent and collaborative working from board level to each area of our business.\n\nIf candidates would like to apply for either of the roles or find out more, they can contact our team on <a class=\"DetectedNumber\" title=\"01829 732615\" href=\"dial:01829732615\">01829 732615</a> or email <a href=\"mailto:recruitment@jigsawmedical.com\">recruitment@jigsawmedical.com</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/teamjigsaw.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-568\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/teamjigsaw.png\" alt=\"teamjigsaw\" width=\"900\" height=\"601\" /></a>', 'New additions and vacancies at #TeamJigsaw...', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'new-additions-and-vacancies-at-teamjigsaw', '', '', '2015-03-12 11:46:26', '2015-03-12 11:46:26', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=709', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1522, 6, '2015-03-13 12:43:31', '2015-03-13 12:43:31', '<div>\n<h1 class=\"quoteText\">“No one has ever become poor by giving.” – Anne Frank.</h1>\nIn order to help celebrate Comic Relief day this year I\'ve decided to take part in the #CEOSelfie campaign.\n\nThe aim of the campaign is for CEOs around the country to help change the face of their business by posting a selfie on the CEO Selfie website (www.ceoselfie.co.uk) and making a donation to Comic Relief.\n\nAs well as directly raising money for the Comic Relief charity it will also help raise awareness of the tireless work that they do, not only on leading up to #RedNoseDay but throughout the year to help tackle poverty and social inequality in the UK and around the world.\n\nSince the charity was formed in 1985 it has raised £950 million the help the above causes, with over 40% of that being spent directly on issues here in the UK.\n\nCharity is an issue close to my heart and it always important to give something back. So much so that here at #TeamJigsaw we have set up our own charitable cause called <a title=\"Jigsaw Foundation\" href=\"Since%20the launch of Jigsaw Medical, Chris has always believed in giving back and supporting charitable causes. Over the years Jigsaw and Chris personally have donated, supported and been involved in countless charitable activities across the country. The Jigsaw Foundation was set up to formalise our charitable aim and allow our team to decide on which charities the company wishes to support each year. We do this a number of ways, including by pledging to donate at least 1% of profits to charity.\" target=\"_blank\">Jigsaw Foundation</a>, which was set up to formalise our charitable aim and allow our team to decide on which charities the company wishes to support each year. We do this a number of ways, including by pledging to donate at least 1% of profits to charity.\n\nSo if there are any other CEOs out there who haven\'t already done so. Get your smartphone, take a #CEOSelfie and upload it to the website...and don\'t forget to donate!!\n\n<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Photo-13-03-2015-09-23-23.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-720\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Photo-13-03-2015-09-23-23.jpg\" alt=\"Chris_Percival_CEOSelfie\" width=\"900\" height=\"1200\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n<div></div>', 'CEO Selfie for Comic Relief', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'ceo-selfie-for-comic-relief', '', '', '2015-03-13 12:43:31', '2015-03-13 12:43:31', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=718', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1523, 6, '2015-04-02 10:27:52', '2015-04-02 10:27:52', '<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<div>\n<h3>After coming out of a meeting with one of my mentees last week it got me thinking about what makes a good mentor and what it means to me to be a mentor.</h3>\nI was asked to become a Virgin Startup Mentor a couple of years ago and have thoroughly enjoyed every moment of it ever since. I love being able to make a real different to people\'s lives and their aspirations in business by providing them with support, guidance and encouragement, as well a few helpful tips that I have learnt along the way!\n\nA good mentor relationship can be deeply rewarding for both parties involved as long as it is done properly. So what makes a good mentor?\n\nThe first key to becoming a good mentor is being genuinely interested in the person you\'re mentoring and to also believe in them personally and professionally. You need to make the effort to understand them and their business which will enable you to mentor them in a way that they need.\n\nThe relationship works both ways, therefore you must have credibility and have achieved some success in the area you are mentoring in otherwise the mentee will not trust your advice and feedback. I may be (quite) young but I like to think that with the things I have already achieved in business I can be seen as credible when mentoring young(er!) entrepreneurs.\n\nThis credibility will help you share your insights and experiences and ensure the mentee will take them aboard. Don\'t be afraid to share any mistakes or tough times you have had in the past; starting and running a business is never always easy-sailing (if you haven\'t had any downs yet they\'re unfortunately to come), however as long as you learn from mistakes and adversity you\'ll always come out the other side better, more determined and, dare-I-say-it, wiser!\n\nProviding feedback and advice is a key part of being a mentor, but choosing the correct type of feedback and delivering at the right time is the challenging. Giving unwelcome feedback or unnecessary advice can be detrimental to morale and can affect the relationship with your mentee.\n\nFinally, always remember to highlight any achievements that the mentee has made; celebrating their successes will help build their confidence and will make the relationship much stronger.\n\nThe most important thing to remember about being a mentor is the fact that every mentee and relationship is different; although the things above can be taken into consideration you have to be flexible and adapt to the person being mentored. Each situation will be different to the next but if done right there’s a lot of enjoyment that can come from watching someone develop and reach their full potential!\n\nWe all need mentors, I’m lucky enough to have very experienced and very inspirational mentors – without whom, Jigsaw would not be what it is today.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>', 'What makes a good mentor?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-make-a-good-mentor', '', '', '2015-04-02 10:27:52', '2015-04-02 10:27:52', '', 0, 'http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/?p=736', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1525, 1, '2017-05-19 15:14:19', '2017-05-19 15:14:19', '<h1>#TeamJigsaw recently welcomed Sam Branson and Noah Devereaux to Jigsaw House to hear about STRIVING  &amp; Big Change...</h1>\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-891\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/15400984_10154247540328262_8689973001302486932_n-1-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />\r\n\r\nAs you may have read, we were proud to have sponsored the <a href=\"http://bigchange.strivechallenge.com/\">Virgin STRIVE Challenge</a> in 2016, raising an incredible seven-figure sum for the charity \'<a href=\"http://big-change.org/\">Big Change</a>\'. As a provider of medical services and one of the key sponsors, I was pleased to welcome Sam &amp; Noah to Jigsaw House, to introduce them to the team and hear about what has been happening since the epic challenge and where the huge amount of money raised will be going.\r\n\r\nNoah spoke to the team about \'growth mindset\' and the purpose of the philosophy and we also heard from Jan (our Head of Compliance, who took part in one of the cycle legs) who although told Sam and I beforehand that she was very nervous and hated public speaking - did an incredible job (so much so, we couldn\'t get her off the stage - so well done Jan!). Then we heard from Kathryn, who coordinated our medical team for the STRIVE challenge, who spoke about working together as a team to look after the participants and help make the event what it was.\r\n\r\nWe had a great day hearing about the incredible cause we have all worked so far to raise such a huge amount of money for and I am very much looking forward to what Sam &amp; Noah think up for the next challenge!', 'Sam Branson & Noah Devereaux Visit Jigsaw House', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '888-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-19 15:14:19', '2017-05-19 15:14:19', '', 888, 'http://localhost/ChrisPercival/2017/05/19/888-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1526, 1, '2017-05-22 10:53:03', '2017-05-22 10:53:03', '<a href=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_5782.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-864\" src=\"http://www.chrispercival.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_5782-247x300.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_5782\" width=\"247\" height=\"300\" /></a>', 'Never Let What You Want, Overshadow What You Have', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '863-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-05-22 10:53:03', '2017-05-22 10:53:03', '', 863, 'http://localhost/ChrisPercival/2017/05/22/863-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
